latestVersion.conditions:
Distributor Requirement:

To request access to a restricted data file from this study, copy this page onto an e-mail with the requested information filled in, and send to Dr. Jane M. Murphy, JMURPHY11@PARTNERS.ORG

1. Your name, address, and academic affiliation.
2. The name of the file(s) you wish to access.
3. A brief description of the use you plan to make of the data.
4. Agreement with the following conditions:

All authorized u sers of the datasets will be required to provide formal acknowledgement of having accepted these terms:

1. The Distributor has granted me a revocable license to use these datasets (dataset names to be inserted) solely for the purposes of conducting research, and the Distributor may terminate this license at any time and for any reason.

2. I will use the datasets solely for statistical analysis and reporting of aggregated information, and not for investigation of specific individuals or organizations.

3. I will produce no links between the Contributor's datasets and other datasets.

4. I represent that neither I, nor anyone I know, has any prior knowledge of the possible identities of an study participants in any data set that I am being licensed to use.

5. I will not knowingly divulge any information that could be used to identify individual participants in the study, nor will I attempt to identify or contact any study participant, and I agree to use any precautions necessary to prevent such identification.
< br /> 6. I will not reproduce the datasets except as is necessary for my scholarly purposes. I will destroy the datasets upon the completion of my scholarly work with them. And I will inform the Contributor that I have done this.

7. I will not share data from the datasets (in any form or by any means) with any third party, including other members of my research team, as I understand that all users of data must obtain the data directly from the Distributor.

BY PLACING MY NAME IN THE SPACE LABELED “SIGNATURE” BELOW I CONFIRM THAT

(A) I HAVE READ AND UNDERSTOOD THE CONDITIONS SET FORTH ABOVE, AND AGREE TO BE BOUND BY THEM.
(B) THE INFORMATION I HAVE PROVIDED IS ACCURATE AND I HA VE THE AUTHORITY TO SIGN THE FORM,
(C) I AGREE TO CONFINE MYSELF TO ANALYSIS OF THE DATA, AND NOT TO REPRODUCE IT, IN ANY FORM, WITHOUT PRIOR EXPRESS WRITTEN CONSENT.

latestVersion.studyCompletion:
As in all survey research, some selected persons have chosen not to be interviewed. The completion rates for the samples and the followed cohorts range between 82% and 92%. These completion rates are based on the number of subjects who completed enough of the interview for a diagnostic algorithm to be applied and for epidemiologic rates based on age and gender to be calculated. The pertinent algorithm is called DPAX-1 (an updated version of which is called DPAX-2). They are described in the section below titled “Nature and Analysis of Psychiatric Information”. The 3,410 subjects shown in the data sets are those who met this criterion of inclusion.

The subjects from a given sample who are not represented in its cohorts are those who died or who were living but did not wish to be re-interviewed. The completion figures of 82% to 92% are based on interviews among the living subjects for the cohorts and on all selected subjects for the samples.

dsDescriptionValue.value:
The Stirling County Study is an ongoing longitudinal investigation of the epidemiology of psychiatric disorders among adults (18 years of age and older) in a general population. The site is a county located in Atlantic Canada for which the fictitious name of “Stirling County” is used to protect identity. The general purpose of the study is to investigate relationships between social environmental factors and epidemiologic rates of psychiatric disorders. The study was started in 1948 by Dr. Alexander H. Leighton (now deceased). Dr. Jane M. Murphy joined the study in 1951 and has directed it since 1975.

These data sets consist of information given in structured interviews by 3,410 subjects who were selected in representative samples of the county at three points in time.

fields.value:
The sampling procedures for the study varied over time. The frame for the first sample was an "nth" selection of households based on research maps that had been enlarged from aerial photographs. Within households, the subjects to be interviewed were selected mainly by alternating male and female heads of households (bread-winner and food-preparer) and accepting into the sequence single-gender households. The frame for the second sample was again an "nth" selection, this time making use of a research census of all adult residents of the county. The third sample was based on computerized random selection from an updated research census. Analys
is has consistently indicated that the samples represent well the adults of the county as a whole.
